  "format": "Episode 7 of Brian Raftery's Vietnam-at-the-movies series, on how Platoon's success set off a late-'80s glut of Vietnam films, and what that boom actually showed (and what it didn't).",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The post-Platoon Vietnam movie boom",
      "note": "the films this episode is built around",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Platoon",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "Oliver Stone's low-budget epic made nearly $140M and set off what one journalist called the Vietnam Vogue."
        },
        {
          "title": "Full Metal Jacket",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "Kubrick's two-part film (Parris Island, then Hue during Tet), shot in cloudy England. R. Lee Ermey's drill sergeant made it a must-see."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hamburger Hill",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "John Irvin's gruesome account of a real battle, shot in the Philippines with Department of Defense cooperation. Flopped in theaters, then became a video-store hit."
        },
        {
          "title": "Paths of Glory",
          "year": 1957,
          "note": "Kubrick's earlier WWI anti-war film with Kirk Douglas; one of Oliver Stone's favorites, banned for years in France and Switzerland."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Deer Hunter",
          "year": 1978,
          "note": "Irvin called it racist and unlike the war he'd witnessed, which is why he wanted to make Hamburger Hill."
        },
        {
          "title": "Good Morning, Vietnam",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "Robin Williams as DJ Adrian Cronauer; sold by Disney as an upbeat romp, it sat at No. 1 for over two months in early 1988."
        },
        {
          "title": "Casualties of War",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Brian De Palma's brutal true-story film with Michael J. Fox and Sean Penn; a box-office failure that found its audience on cable and home video."
        },
        {
          "title": "Apocalypse Now",
          "year": 1979,
          "note": "Michael Herr wrote its narration; a cable and VHS staple that hooked a generation of underage viewers."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Green Berets",
          "year": 1968,
          "note": "John Wayne's pro-war film, mocked by the Marines in Gustav Hasford's The Short Timers."
        },
        {
          "title": "Coming Home",
          "year": 1978,
          "note": "Cited as the kind of tough reckoning with the war that Good Morning Vietnam wasn't."
        },
        {
          "title": "Welcome Home",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Drama about a presumed-dead vet (Kris Kristofferson); Kieu Chinh plays his Cambodian wife, then vanishes from the film."
        }
      ]
    }
